“Ain’t no fun when the rabbit got the gun.”

It’s an old Southern/American proverb-like expression meaning:

People often enjoy a power imbalance—until the balance flips.

The rabbit is normally the hunted. The hunter has the gun.

When the rabbit has the gun, everything changes.

It can imply:

* Don’t underestimate the underdog.
* Power changes perspective.
* Fairness is easier to preach when you’re winning.
* Those who dish it out often dislike receiving the same treatment.
* Every advantage can reverse.

It’s similar in spirit to:

* “Turnabout is fair play.”
* “Tables have turned.”
* “The hunter becomes the hunted.”
* “Live by the sword, die by the sword.”

Given the themes we’ve been discussing, it also works metaphorically for ideas:

The student surpasses the teacher.

The tool begins revealing patterns to its creator.

The once-overlooked framework becomes the one others learn from.

It’s a memorable way of expressing a reversal of roles or leverage.